# Budget Monorepo Core Conventions

## Architecture priorities

- Keep domain logic independent from UI and transport layers.
- Model imported transactions as immutable source records.
- Store user edits as overlays (category override, split, hide flag, notes).
- Prefer additive schema evolution over destructive rewrites.

## Shared library boundaries

- Keep shared data models, interfaces, classes, and domain definitions in a common library folder outside `api` and `client`.
- Treat `api` and `client` as consumers of shared contracts, not owners of core domain types.
- If a type is needed by more than one app/package, move it to the common library immediately.
- Keep transport-specific DTOs at boundaries, then map to shared domain models in services.

## Backend/API conventions

- Validate request payloads at boundaries and return typed errors.
- Avoid route handlers with business logic; delegate to services.
- Use explicit names for money and dates (`amountCents`, `postedAt`, `monthKey`).

## Client conventions

- Keep components presentational where possible; move stateful logic to hooks/services.
- Make uncertain automations reviewable (confidence score + review queue UX).
- Favor optimistic UI only when rollback behavior is clearly defined.

## Data model guidance

- Start with entities: account, transaction, merchant, category, rule, budget, goal.
- Keep categorization rules deterministic and auditable.
- Track source metadata for imports (provider, account ref, import timestamp).

## Quality bar

- Add or update tests for changed business behavior.
- Include short notes in PRs/commits describing trade-offs in data model decisions.
